==English==

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{term|abreggen||curtail, lessen|lang=enm}}, {{term|abregge|lang=enm}}, {{term|abrigge|lang=enm}},<ref> {{R:RHCD|page=5}}</ref> from {{etyl|fro|en}} {{term|abregier||lang=fro}} {{term|abreger||lang=fro}}, from {{etyl|LL.|en}} {{term|abbrevio||make brief|lang=la}}, from {{etyl|la|en}} {{term|ad||lang=la}} + {{m|la|brēvio||shorten}}.<ref>{{R:MW3 1976|page=6}}</ref>

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|RP}} {{IPA|/əˈbrɪd͡ʒ/|lang=en}}
* {{a|US}} {{IPA|/əˈbrɪd͡ʒ/|lang=en}}
* {{audio|en-us-abridge.ogg|Audio (US)|lang=en}}
* {{rhymes|ɪdʒ|lang=en}}

===Verb===
{{en-verb|abridg}}

# {{context|transitive|archaic|lang=en}} To [[deprive]]; to [[cut off]]. {{defdate|First attested from around (1150 to 1350)}}<ref name=SOED>{{R:SOED5|page=8}}</ref>
# {{context|transitive|archaic|rare|lang=en}} To [[debar]] from. {{defdate|First attested from around (1150 to 1350)}}<ref name=SOED/>
# {{context|transitive|lang=en}} To make [[shorter]]; to [[shorten]] in [[duration]] or [[extent]]. {{defdate|First attested from around (1350 to 1470)}}<ref name=SOED/>
#* The bridegroom ... '''abridged''' his visit. - Smollett
#* She retired herself to Sebaste, and '''abridged''' her train from state to necessity. - Fuller
# {{context|transitive|lang=en}} To shorten or contract by using [[fewer]] [[word]]s, yet [[retaining]] the [[sense]]; to [[epitomize]]; to [[condense]]; as, to '''abridge''' a [[history]] or [[dictionary]]. {{defdate|First attested in 1384.}}<ref>{{R:CDOE|page=4}}</ref>. {{defdate|First attested from around (1350 to 1470)}}<ref name=SOED/>
# {{context|transitive|lang=en}} Cut short; [[truncate]]. {{defdate|First attested from around (1350 to 1470)}}<ref name=SOED/>
# {{context|transitive|lang=en}} To [[curtail]]. {{defdate|First attested from around (1350 to 1470)}}<ref name=SOED/>
#: ''He had his rights '''abridged''' by the crooked sheriff.''

====Usage notes====
* {{sense|deprive}} Usually used with '''to''' or sometimes with '''from''' as, to '''abridge''' one of his rights.

